dashingWeather

Mohammad Hamdan

June 2, 2023

Introduction

dashingWeather is a weather app created using Dash for Python. The user can use this app to access an influx of weather information about any city in the entire world, including the current conditions, temperature, rain, wind speed and more, as well as as a forecast for the next 5 days. Furthermore, there is also a colourful world map which visualizes current weather conditions across the globe, from temperature to wind or precipitation.

Accessing the app

In order to download the app, you must run this code in the terminal on your computer (don’t forget to first set it to the directory you want the app in!)

pip install git+git://github.com/themohammadhamdan/dashingWeather.git

You must then go into the module folder and open app.py. Run the code (this can be done by clicking on the green play button if you’re using PyCharm). In the Python console you should then see where the app is being broadcast to (this should be a series of numbers in this format: http://XXX.X.X.X:XXXX/). Click on the numbers, and you should then be redirected to your browser and be able to use dashingWeather.

Launch

At launch, the user is greeted by the current conditions for Amsterdam, The Netherlands (which is where the app was developed). Data is displayed in metric measurements (again, to reflect where the app was made), so temperatures are presented in degrees Celsius (°C), and wind speeds are presented in meters per second. The world map is set to display world temperatures.

The user is exposed to a useful amount of real-time weather information for Amsterdam, including sunrise and sunset times, as well as humidity levels and cloudiness percentage. They can also see the forecast for temperatures and rain (in mm) for Amsterdam over the next five days. Surprisingly there is no rain for Amsterdam according to this forecast! Furthermore, they can also see various metrics from the forecast for tomorrow’s weather, including the temperature and what it will feel like.

Features

City change

From there the user has the freedom to to look up weather conditions in any city of their choice, where the only limits are their speed of typing. They can go about this by typing in the name of a city in the search bar and clicking the on-screen Go button, or the Enter button their keyboard. Let’s look at a city on a different continent, perhaps Cairo, Egypt:

The entire webpage is then instantly updated to show the metrics for Cairo from right now and for the next few days.

This includes a change in the dynamic icon: a flag icon which also updates whenever a new city (or a city in a different country) is typed in! Notice how the Dutch flag switched to the Egyptian flag?

Measurement change

An important part about this app is that it is inclusive of Americans that refuse to use the same units of measurement as the rest of us. Let’s switch the display to New York.

The average American will have no clue what 11°C means, they’ll probably think it is freezing cold in New York right now! Let’s switch our units to a format that they can interpret. For everyone living in the rest of the world, 59°F seems insanely hot, but now Americans can understand what’s happening. Plus they can look at their beloved flag.

Interactive Plots

The temperature and rain plots are interactive, allowing the user to zoom in and out and even save them as .png files if they wish.

World view

Last but not least, using the app the user can access colourful images that tell them about the state of the weather across the world today:

For example, they can see how temperature is distributed across the globe, or how windy it is or where it will rain now. It is currently late spring in the northern hemisphere so there will be warmer temperatures, less wind and rain above the equator, and vice versa below it. However, with climate change there is no guarantee, so if something seems off on the app (like rain in Cairo but not in Amsterdam), blame climate change, not me!

Contact

Lastly, at the bottom right of the screen, users are presented with different ways to contact the developer - simply by clicking the app icon of their interest: they can contact me through Twitter or Linkedin, and by checking out my Github they can also find the code that runs the app.
